         The Company's average investment in mortgage loans and fixed income
securities was $1.2 billion during 1992 reflecting an increase of approximately
$70 million over 1991.  Revenues generated from these assets consist
principally of mortgage loan interest, which is included in interest, charges
and fees on loans, and bond interest, which is included in investment income.

         Interest, charges and fees on loans increased $2.4 million in 1992.
The Company's average loan portfolio was approximately $540 million during 1992
compared to $560 million during 1991.  During 1992 and 1991, the Company sold
approximately $272 million and $162 million, respectively, in home equity loans
and recognized approximately $12.1 million and $8.8 million, respectively, in
net loan origination fees in connection with these sales.  In addition, net
loan origination fees increased approximately $1.3 million in 1992 primarily as
a result of an increase in loan production.

